                                                                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="15834492" author="tallison@mitre.org" created="Mon, 23 Jan 2017 13:35:56 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Y, Tika doesn&apos;t currently maintain table format because tables aren&apos;t stored as such in PDFs.  You have to apply some serious math to figure out 1) where a table is and 2) where the columns are, etc. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Have you tried &lt;a href=&quot;http://tabula.technology/&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;TabulaPDF&lt;/a&gt;?  See also the &lt;a href=&quot;http://contentmine.org/&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;ContentMine&lt;/a&gt;&apos;s recent work with tables (&lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/petermurrayrust/status/823450517212905472&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;twitter&lt;/a&gt;).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;To attach a file, did you go to More-&amp;gt;Attach Files?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15834661" author="devilsuse" created="Mon, 23 Jan 2017 14:32:27 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;So when Tika claims to parse pdf to HTML and in the resultant HTML if tables are not preserved i.e. no table tags then isn&apos;t it wrong?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thanks for showing where to attach file. Done &lt;img class=&quot;emoticon&quot; src=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/images/icons/emoticons/smile.png&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot; align=&quot;absmiddle&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15834681" author="tallison@mitre.org" created="Mon, 23 Jan 2017 14:41:45 +0000"  >&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;So when Tika claims to parse pdf to HTML and in the resultant HTML if tables are not preserved i.e. no table tags then isn&apos;t it wrong?&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This hinges on &quot;tables are not preserved.&quot;  There are no tables in the underlying PDF document to be preserved.   There are instructions for where to draw lines and where to place text on the page.  Humans can very easily see tables.  It takes computation that Tika doesn&apos;t currently apply to &quot;guess&quot; where the tables are and what the rows/columns contain.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We should update our documentation to acknowledge this limitation, and if you can recommend an Apache 2.0-friendly package that extracts tables, we can work towards integrating that functionality (perhaps grobid+Tabula?).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;MSWord documents and rtf documents, by contrast, store tables as objects that we can programmatically process and &quot;preserve&quot; the structure of those tables.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15834702" author="tallison@mitre.org" created="Mon, 23 Jan 2017 14:57:36 +0000"  >&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;We should update our documentation to acknowledge this limitation.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Please let us know where we should update this.  Definitely in the javadoc for the PDFParser...where else?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15836087" author="devilsuse" created="Tue, 24 Jan 2017 12:24:39 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=tallison%40mitre.org&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;tallison@mitre.org&quot;&gt;tallison@mitre.org&lt;/a&gt; - Got it. I thought tables are stored as &quot;identifiable objects&quot; and TIKA isn&apos;t able to extract that.. So that&apos;s not the case- now I know. Is there a place where I can find any facts about how to identify different elements in PDF so that they can then be converted into html format, sort of how to implement it, how PDF stores data internally etc. I know I can google it but if you already know some useful links that would be helpful.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Regarding enhancing documents - yes it should definitely be part of documentation. It should be placed both in javadocs and in tutorials. Because most of developers need to actually look up into javadoc for using TIKA, its so straightforward and easy to use. links to be modified would be &lt;a href=&quot;https://tika.apache.org/1.14/examples.htm&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://tika.apache.org/1.14/examples.htm&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=&quot;https://tika.apache.org/1.14/api/&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://tika.apache.org/1.14/api/&lt;/a&gt; .&lt;br/&gt;
And may be linking to this JIRA in docs for curious developer will be helpful so that he knows the background of why does this limitation exists in TIKA.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15836601" author="tallison@mitre.org" created="Tue, 24 Jan 2017 20:39:05 +0000"  >&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;Is there a place where I can find any facts about how to identify different elements in PDF so that they can then be converted into html format, sort of how to implement it, how PDF stores data internally etc&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Well...there&apos;s the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.adobe.com/content/dam/Adobe/en/devnet/acrobat/pdfs/pdf_reference_1-7.pdf&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;PDF spec&lt;/a&gt;, all 1310 pages of it.  You could take a look at our &lt;tt&gt;PDFParser&lt;/tt&gt;, &lt;tt&gt;PDF2XHTML&lt;/tt&gt; (including &lt;tt&gt;AbstractPDF2XHTML&lt;/tt&gt;), and of course &lt;tt&gt;PDFTextStripper&lt;/tt&gt;.  &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;What, specifically, are you trying to pull out?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15836610" author="tallison@mitre.org" created="Tue, 24 Jan 2017 20:45:12 +0000"  >&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://tika.apache.org/1.14/examples.html&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://tika.apache.org/1.14/examples.html&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=&quot;https://tika.apache.org/1.14/api/&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://tika.apache.org/1.14/api/&lt;/a&gt; .&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I worry that both of these are high-level overviews.  I&apos;d prefer not to include parser-specific warnings there, unless you see something there that alleges we extract tables/structure out of documents...we allude to it via the xhtml, but we don&apos;t claim to get everything...perhaps I&apos;m misreading?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;How about on our &lt;a href=&quot;https://wiki.apache.org/tika/PDFParser%20%28Apache%20PDFBox%29&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;wiki&lt;/a&gt;?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15836614" author="hudson" created="Tue, 24 Jan 2017 20:47:38 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;SUCCESS: Integrated in Jenkins build Tika-trunk #1188 (See &lt;a href=&quot;https://builds.apache.org/job/Tika-trunk/1188/&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://builds.apache.org/job/Tika-trunk/1188/&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/TIKA-2249&quot; title=&quot;Tika not able to parse tables from pdf &quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;TIKA-2249&quot;&gt;TIKA-2249&lt;/a&gt; &amp;#8211; update javadocs to alert devs that tables are not (tallison: rev fe94908c052dd70fb9f1c3e369a3547b335d8760)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;(edit) tika-parsers/src/main/java/org/apache/tika/parser/pdf/PDFParser.java&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
</comment>
                            <comment id="15836618" author="hudson" created="Tue, 24 Jan 2017 20:49:52 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;SUCCESS: Integrated in Jenkins build tika-2.x #207 (See &lt;a href=&quot;https://builds.apache.org/job/tika-2.x/207/&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://builds.apache.org/job/tika-2.x/207/&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/TIKA-2249&quot; title=&quot;Tika not able to parse tables from pdf &quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;TIKA-2249&quot;&gt;TIKA-2249&lt;/a&gt; &amp;#8211; update javadocs to alert devs that tables are not (tallison: rev 235c2adab1d1ad986b177c1c1fe48c2a4b13a4e7)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;(edit) tika-parser-modules/tika-parser-multimedia-module/src/main/java/org/apache/tika/parser/pdf/PDFParser.java&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
</comment>
                            <comment id="15848246" author="devilsuse" created="Wed, 1 Feb 2017 11:21:28 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=tallison%40mitre.org&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;tallison@mitre.org&quot;&gt;tallison@mitre.org&lt;/a&gt; : I tried Aspose.Pdf for Java(free trial version), it works quite well in converting pdf into html. To use it seemlessly I would have to buy the license, ahhh... Just wished we could have such solutions in open source as well. Definitely Aspose team has done something which Tika is lacking and can build upon.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;They provide lots of option like save html file with image embedded, the converted html file maintains table structure and other structures intact.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Also not many developers land-up on wiki if they get required code on the links I mentioned earlier. The limitation of table extraction therefore should at the places which would actually be frequented by developers. Keeping that &quot;also&quot; on wiki is nice But only on wiki is not so helpful IMHO.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15848295" author="tallison@mitre.org" created="Wed, 1 Feb 2017 12:09:18 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Our github site is always open...patches/pull requests are welcomed. &lt;img class=&quot;emoticon&quot; src=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/images/icons/emoticons/wink.png&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot; align=&quot;absmiddle&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
